<article>
    <h1>A Se&#xAD;cret Gar&#xAD;den</h1>
    <h2>Sculp&#xAD;tures by Tai&#xAD;wanese artist Lee Kuang-yu float across the Cloud For&#xAD;est in a new show</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200808/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-08"><time>2020-08-08</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE HOME AND GARDEN</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chan&#xAD;tal Sa&#xAD;jan&#xD;&#xA;Se&#xAD;nior Correspond&#xAD;ent chan&#xAD;tal@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Vis­i­tors to the Cloud For­est will find them­selves step­ping into a Sculp­tor’s Se­cret Gar­den with themes that seem to have popped out of the pages of Bio­philia.</p>
    <p>The 1984 book – by Amer­i­can bi­ol­o­gist and Pulitzer Prize-win­ning author Ed­ward O. Wil­son – pop­u­larised the no­tion that hu­mans have an in­nate need to con­nect with na­ture.</p>
    <p>This can be seen in bio­philic cities which in­te­grate na­ture into ar­chi­tec­ture and town plan­ning.</p>
    <p>Few have a more in­ti­mate con­nec­tion with na­ture than Tai­wanese artist and sculp­tor Lee Kuang-yu, 66. He has an en­tire stu­dio nes­tled in the moun­tains of Xizhi in Taipei, Tai­wan, where he works in bliss­ful soli­tude sculpt­ing, sketch­ing and ex­per­i­ment­ing.</p>
    <p>Gar­dens by the Bay’s Cloud For­est will fea­ture 16 of his sculp­tures based on three themes: A Quiet Respite in the Gar­den, Beau­ti­ful Mem­o­ries, and Man and Na­ture as One.</p>
    <p>Born in 1954 in Kaoh­si­ung, Lee grad­u­ated from the Sculp­ture Depart­ment of Tai­wan’s Na­tional Academy of the Arts in 1975. He went on to pur­sue West­ern sculp­tural tech­niques and the­ory in Spain’s Real Academia de Bel­las Artes de San Fer­nando and Univer­si­dad Com­plutense de Madrid.</p>
    <p>He re­turned to Tai­wan in 1984 and taught at the Taipei Na­tional Univer­sity of the Arts and the Na­tional Tai­wan Univer­sity of Arts. Af­ter re­tir­ing in 2006, he de­voted him­self to his art prac­tice.</p>
    <p>In Oc­to­ber 2018, Lee vis­ited the Cloud For­est for the first time.</p>
    <p>His visit in­spired him to show the union of sculp­ture and gar­den, and the re­la­tion­ship be­tween the two which, he says, “el­e­vates the over­all am­bi­ence”.</p>
    <p>“My cre­ative in­spi­ra­tion has al­ways come from gar­dens. This ex­hi­bi­tion has deep­ened my un­der­stand­ing of sculp­ture, which, like a gar­den, can bloom splen­didly and touches one’s heart with happiness.”</p>
    <p>Re­cent Gar­dens vis­i­tor Se­bas­tian Lau was par­tic­u­larly drawn to the work called Empty Pro­ces­sion – of a woman danc­ing on a tor­toise – which he says re­minds him of fairies and nymphs in Chi­nese myths.</p>
    <p>“De­pend­ing on where you stand at the ex­hibit, which is near a re­flect­ing pool, you seem to get dif­fer­ent im­ages of a sin­gle sculp­ture,” says Mr Lau, a reg­u­la­tory in­spec­tor at Sin­ga­pore’s Health Sciences Au­thor­ity who is in his 40s.</p>

